	<h3>TULIP</h3>
	<img src="images/tulip.jpg" alt="Tulip" width="200" /><br>
	
	<p>DETAILS
	
Scientific Classification: Tulips belong to the genus Tulipa in the lily family (Liliaceae). They are perennial, bulbous plants.

Appearance: Known for their cup-shaped blooms, tulips come in a wide range of colors, including red, yellow, pink, purple, and white.

Origin: Native to Central Asia, tulips were introduced to Europe in the 16th century and became a symbol of wealth during the Dutch Golden Age.

Cultivation: Tulips thrive in well-drained soil and prefer full sun or partial shade. They bloom in spring and are often planted in the fall.

BENEFITS 

Medicinal Properties: Tulips have been traditionally used to treat ailments like headaches, colds, and digestive issues. Modern research highlights their anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties2.

Skin Benefits: Tulip extracts are used in cosmetics for their anti-aging and skin-regenerating properties.

Stress Relief: Tulips, like other flowering plants, can help reduce stress and anxiety.

Edible Uses: Tulip petals are edible and can be used in salads or as garnishes.

Aesthetic Appeal: Their vibrant colors and elegant shapes make them a favorite for gardens and floral arrangements.</p>
